Z=-2.In contrast to brushed DC motor, with BLDC motors the permanent magnets are part of the rotor (figure … b) instead of the stator (figure .. a). In this experiment the motors were controlled with a sinusoidal approach, the motor has three windings, a sinusoidal current is applied to each winding with a difference in phase.

The haptic feedback was designed as a combination of force angle (position) and force intensity. The force angle was related to the relative angle (position) of the motor. Constant stimuli were designed with a constant difference in force angle and relative angle. A force angle opposite from the direction of rotation results in friction, whereas a force angle similar to the direction of rotation results in acceleration. Two different effects were used for the design of the switches, a spring and a barrier. The spring effect was designed with a varying difference between the relative position and the force angle, based on the distance between the start point of the effect and the relative position of the motor. The barrier effect, simulates the sense of hitting a hard stop, was designed in a similar way, however the difference between relative angle of the motor and the force angle was smaller and constant when the relative angle has passed the start point of the effect. For both effects a maximum force intensity was applied. Consequently, detents had a sinusoidal force pattern, while the force angle was positioned towards the detent closest to the relative position of the motor to resemble the effect of mechanical steps.

The haptic feedback stimuli were designed with the aid of an editor and uploaded to both microcontrollers, where they were translated to a 12-bit PWM signal with a 20kHz frequency, with an update rate of 1200Hz.
